# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ferrite-bead
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] A **balun** /ˈbælʌn/ (from "balanced to unbalanced", originally, but now derived from "**balancing unit**") is an electrical device that allows balanced and unbalanced lines to be interfaced without disturbing the impedance arrangement of either line.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] A balun can take many forms and may include devices that also transform impedances but need not do so.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Sometimes, in the case of transformer baluns, they use magnetic coupling but need not do so.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Common-mode chokes are also used as baluns and work by eliminating, rather than rejecting, common mode signals.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] In classical transformers, there are two electrically separate windings of wire coils around the transformer's core.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] This type is sometimes called a 'voltage balun'.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The primary winding receives the input signal, and the secondary winding puts out the converted signal.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The core that they are wound on may either be empty (air core) or, equivalently, a magnetically neutral material like a porcelain support, or it may be a material which is good magnetic conductor like ferrite in modern high-frequency (HF) baluns, or soft iron as in the early days of telegraphy.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The electrical signal in the primary coil is converted into a magnetic field in the transformer's core.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] When the electrical current through the primary reverses, it causes the established magnetic field to collapse.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The collapsing magnetic field then induces an electric field in the secondary winding.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The ratio of loops in each winding and the efficiency of the coils' magnetic coupling determines the ratio of electrical potential (voltage) to electrical current and the total power of the output.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] For idealized transformers, although the ratio of voltage to current will change in exact proportion to the square of the winding ratio, the power (measured in watts) remains identical.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] In real transformers, some energy is lost inside to heating of the metallic core of the transformer, to the AC and DC resistances of the winding conductors, and lost outside to the surrounding environment because of imperfect magnetic coupling between the two coils.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] An ideal balun consists of two wires (primary and secondary) and a core: the current in the primary wire generates a magnetic field in the core, which in turn induces an electric field in the secondary wire.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] An autotransformer balun has only one coil, or is made of two or more coils that have an electrical connection, wound around a core.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] One can also make an autotransformer from an ordinary transformer by cross-wiring the primary and secondary windings.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Baluns made with autotransformer windings are also called *voltage baluns*, since they produce balanced output voltage, but not necessarily balanced current.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] In all autotransformers, the single winding must have at least one extra electrical connection – called a *tap* or *tap point* – between the two ends of the winding.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The current sent into the balun through one pair of connections acts as if it were a primary coil, and magnetizes the entire core.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] When the electric current in the input segment of the coil changes, the induced magnetic field collapses and the collapse of the magnetic field in the core induces an electric current in the entire coil.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Electrical connections to parts of the coil different from the input connections have higher or lower voltages depending on the length of the coil that the output is tapped from.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Unlike transformer-type baluns, an autotransformer balun provides a path for DC current to ground from every terminal.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Since outdoor antennas are prone to build-up of static electric charge, the path for the static to drain to ground through an autotransformer balun can be a distinct advantage.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Transmission line or *choke* baluns can be considered as simple forms of transmission line transformers.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] This type is sometimes called a *current balun*, since it ensures equal current on both sides of its output, but not necessarily equal voltage.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] These are normally called ununs, because they go from unbalanced to unbalanced or un-un.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Baluns are balanced to unbalanced or bal-un.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] A more subtle type results when the transformer type (magnetic coupling) is combined with the transmission line type (electro-magnetic coupling).
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Most typically the same kind of transmission line wires are used for the windings as carry the signal from the radio to the antenna, although these baluns can be made using any type of wire.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The resulting devices have very wideband operation.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] *Transmission line transformers* commonly use small ferrite cores in toroidal rings or two-hole, binocular, shapes.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The Guanella transmission line transformer (Guanella 1944) is often combined with a balun to act as an impedance matching transformer.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Putting balancing aside a transformer of this type consists of a 75 Ω transmission line divided in parallel into two 150 Ω cables, which are then combined in series for 300 Ω.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] It is implemented as a specific wiring around the ferrite core of the balun.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Classic magnetic transformers are limited in maximum frequency due to the permeability of the magnetic material, which declines rapidly above MHz frequencies.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] This limits the operating frequency to around 1 GHz.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Microwave systems require baluns in the 1-100 GHz range for applications including mixers, push-pull amplifiers, and interface to differential analog to digital and digital to analog converters.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Transmission line transformer baluns with a high frequency transmission line such as a wirewound pair are able to operate at significantly higher frequencies (to 8 GHz and above) by combining capacitive coupling with magnetic coupling typical of classic magnetic transformers.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] To operate at even higher frequencies, magnetic loading becomes ineffective.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Nathan Marchand proposed a 'conversion transformer' that was capable of operation over a 1:3 bandwidth ratio in 1944.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] This basic circuit has been widely adapted and modified for use in planar structures (such as MMICs and RFICs) at frequencies up to at least 100 GHz.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] These types of planar baluns work exciting a mode in a ground plane or shield, which is then 'floated' away from the main ground.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] This allows extraction of the negative signal in addition to the main transmission line, creating positive and negative signal pairs.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] By connecting the positive and negative signal paths in various configurations dozens of balun configurations have been proposed and published in the electronics literature.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The electrical connection of capacitance and inductance leads to a frequency where the electrical reactance of the self-inductance and self-capacitance in the balun are equal in magnitude but opposite in sign: that is, to resonance.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] A balun of any design operates poorly at or above its self-resonant frequency, and some of the design considerations for baluns are for the purpose of making the resonant frequency as far above the operating frequency as possible.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] An RF choke can be used in place of a balun.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] If a coil is made using coaxial cable near to the feed point of a balanced antenna, then the RF current that flows on the outer surface of the coaxial cable can be attenuated.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] One way of doing this would be to pass the cable through a ferrite toroid.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The end result is exactly the same as a 1:1 current balun (or Guanella-type balun).
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] A balun's function is generally to achieve compatibility between systems, and as such, finds extensive application in modern communications, particularly in realising frequency conversion mixers to make cellular phone and data transmission networks possible.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] They are also used to send an E1 carrier signal from coaxial cable (BNC connector, 1.0/2.3 connector, 1.6/5.6 connector, Type 43 connectors) to UTP CAT-5 cable or IDC connector.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] In television, amateur radio, and other antenna installations and connections, baluns convert between impedances and symmetry of feedlines and antennas.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] For example, transformation of 300-Ω twin-lead or 450-Ω ladder line (balanced) to 75-Ω coaxial cable (unbalanced), or to directly connect a balanced antenna to unbalanced coaxial cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] To avoid feed line radiation, baluns are typically used as a form of common mode choke attached at the antenna feed point to prevent the coaxial cable from acting as an antenna and radiating power.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] This typically is needed when a balanced antenna (for instance, a dipole) is fed with coax; without a balun, the shield of the coax could couple with one side of the dipole, inducing common mode current, and becoming part of the antenna and unintentionally radiating.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] In measuring the impedance or radiation pattern of a balanced antenna using a coaxial cable, it is important to place a balun between the cable and the antenna feed.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Unbalanced currents that may otherwise flow on the cable will make the measured antenna impedance sensitive to the configuration of the feed cable, and the radiation pattern of small antennas may be distorted by radiation from the cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Baluns are present in radars, transmitters, satellites, in every telephone network, and probably in most wireless network modem/routers used in homes.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] It can be combined with transimpedance amplifiers to compose high-voltage amplifiers out of low-voltage components.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Baseband video uses frequencies up to several megahertz.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] A balun can be used to couple video signals to twisted-pair cables instead of using coaxial cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Many security cameras now have both a balanced unshielded twisted pair (UTP) output and an unbalanced coaxial one via an internal balun.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] A balun is also used on the video recorder end to convert back from the 100 Ω balanced to 75 Ω unbalanced.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] A balun of this type has a BNC connector with two screw terminals.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] VGA/DVI baluns are baluns with electronic circuitry used to connect VGA/DVI sources (laptop, DVD, etc.) to VGA/DVI display devices over long runs of CAT-5/CAT-6 cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Runs over 130 m (400 ft) may lose quality because of attenuation and variations in the arrival time of each signal.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] A skew control and special low skew or skew free cable is used for runs over 130 m (400 ft).
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] In audio applications, baluns serve multiple purposes: they can convert between high-impedance unbalanced and low impedance balanced lines.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Another application is decoupling of devices (avoidance of earth loops).
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] A third application of baluns in audio systems is in the provision of balanced mains power to the equipment.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] This noise infiltrates the audio/video system through the power supplies and raises the noise floor of the entire system.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] Except for the connections, the three devices in the image are electrically identical, but only the leftmost two can be used as baluns.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The device on the left would normally be used to connect a high impedance source, such as a guitar, into a balanced microphone input, serving as a passive DI unit.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The one in the center is for connecting a low impedance balanced source, such as a microphone, into a guitar amplifier.
[src:ferrite-bead/balun] The one at the right is not a balun, as it provides only impedance matching.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] A **braid-breaker** is a filter that prevents television interference (TVI).
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] In many cases, TVI is caused by a high field strength of a nearby high frequency (HF) transmitter, the aerial down lead plugged into the back of the TV acts as a longwire antenna or as a simple vertical element.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] The radio frequency (RF) current flowing through the tuner of the TV tends to generate harmonics which then spoil the viewing.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] The braid breaker works by preventing RF signals picked up on the outside flowing into the TV set, while passing RF inside the coax from the antenna.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] Designs for diminishing unwanted signals are based on two types of filters: a “choke” filter which blocks signals in the electrical *mode* most interference uses, and filters that selectively admit or impede signals depending on the signal frequency.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] Further, carefully chosen combinations of filters of either one type or both types multiply each other's effects, so that even if only slightly different, two filters are more effective than a single filter, or either filter alone.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] Ferrite ring chokes work by presenting a high impedance to signals traveling along the braid only, but passes through differential-mode ("balanced") currents unchanged.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] The wanted signal is in differential mode with an equal and opposite current flowing in the braid to that in the cable core.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] The alternating current in the braid is impeded by the magnetic fields created in the ferrite, effectively placing a large inductance in series with the braid.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] The currents from the wanted signal, however, produce equal and opposite magnetic flux in the ferrite which cancel out.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] The device is called a "choke" because the ferrite in effect "chokes off" the signal path for interference.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] The other type of filters used are based on frequency: Below their operating frequency limit, inductors (coils) impede signals at higher frequencies more, and admit low frequencies, whereas capacitors do the opposite: capacitors admit high frequencies but impede low frequencies.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] These can be played-off against each other to impede or admit signals based on frequency.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] A simple design for a high-pass filter consists of two 4.7 pF ceramic capacitors and two simple air-core inductor coils (4 turns of 20 AWG copper wire wound using a 6 mm drill bit as a form).
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] The design is a symmetric network: The line is cut and the coils are connected from the braid to the core of the coaxial cable ends, while the capacitors bridge the cut, one capacitor connecting core-to-core and the other reconnecting the cut outer shield braids.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] As an extra precaution, a 1.5 MΩ resistor is wired in parallel with the capacitor connecting the shields.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] The resistor acts as a “slow leak” on the ground wire that prevents buildup of static electricity on the TV aerial, but is too high a resistance to pass a signal carried along the cable, which operates near 72 Ω.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] The impedance of the capacitors is very large for shortwave signals, below 50 MHz, but for UHF TV signals above 450 MHz their impedance is very small.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] In the opposite sense, the impedance of the coils connecting the inner and outer wires at the lower frequencies is very small, while for the wanted UHF signals the coils have a very high impedance.
[src:ferrite-bead/braid-breaker] An even better option is to use both a choke and a high-pass filter, since the filter described above may not be as effective for common-mode currents, which the choke will selectively remove.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] A **cable tie** (also known as a **hose tie**, **panduit**, **tie wrap**, **wire tie**, or **zip tie**) is a type of fastener for holding items together, primarily electrical cables and wires.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Because of their low cost, ease of use, and binding strength, cable ties are ubiquitous, finding use in a wide range of other applications.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Cable ties were first manufactured by Thomas & Betts under the brand name **Ty-Rap**.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] The common cable tie, normally made of nylon, has a flexible tape section with teeth that engage with a pawl in the head to form a ratchet so that as the free end of the tape section is pulled the cable tie tightens and does not come undone.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] When the mouthpiece is inserted through the grooves and pulled tight, it creates a secure, adjustable loop, which locks in place like a knot.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Some ties include a tab that can be depressed to release the ratchet so that the tie can be loosened or removed, and possibly reused.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Stainless steel versions, some coated with rugged plastic, have been developed for exterior applications and hazardous environments.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] The most common cable tie comprises a flexible nylon tape with an integrated linear ratchet gear rack, and on one end a pawl within a small open case.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Once the pointed tip of the cable tie has been pulled through the case and past the ratchet, it is prevented from being pulled back unless a large amount of force is applied; the resulting loop may only be pulled tighter.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] This allows several cables to be bound into a cable bundle and/or to form a cable tree.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] A cable tie tensioning device or tool may apply a cable tie with a specific tension.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] The tool may cut off the extra tail flush with the head in order to avoid a sharp edge which might otherwise cause injury.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Light-duty tools are operated by squeezing the handle with the fingers, while heavy-duty versions can be powered by compressed air or a solenoid to prevent repetitive strain injury.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] To increase resistance to ultraviolet light in outdoor applications, nylon containing a minimum of 2% carbon black is used to protect the polymer chains and extend the cable tie's service life.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Blue cable ties are supplied to the food industry and contain a metal additive so they can be detected by industrial metal detectors.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Cable ties made of ETFE (Tefzel) are used in radiation-rich environments.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Red cable ties made of ECTFE (Halar) are used for plenum cabling.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Stainless steel cable ties are also available for flameproof applications—coated stainless ties are available to prevent galvanic attack from dissimilar metals (e.g. zinc-coated cable tray).
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Plastic handcuffs are based on the cable tie design and are used by law enforcement to restrain prisoners.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Cable ties are also sometimes used to prevent hubcaps (also known as wheel trims) from falling off a moving vehicle, and some are sold specifically for this purpose.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] The use of cable ties in medicolegal cases is infrequent, being involved in situations of neck compression or restraint.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Cable ties were invented by Thomas & Betts, an electrical company, in 1958 under the brand name Ty-Rap.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Initially, they were designed for airplane wire harnesses.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] The original design used a metal tooth, and these can still be obtained.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Manufacturers later changed to the nylon/plastic design.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Over the years the design has been extended and developed into many spin-off products.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] One example was a self-locking loop developed as an alternative to purse-string suture in colon anastomosis.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] The Ty-Rap cable tie's inventor, Maurus C.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Logan, worked for Thomas & Betts and finished his career with the company as Vice President of Research and Development.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] During his tenure at Thomas & Betts, he contributed to the development and marketing of many successful Thomas & Betts products.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Logan died on 12 November 2007, at age 86.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] The idea for the cable tie came to Logan while touring a Boeing aircraft manufacturing facility in 1956.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Aircraft wiring was a cumbersome and detailed undertaking, involving thousands of feet of wire organized on sheets of 50-foot-long plywood and held in place with knotted, wax-coated, braided nylon cord.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Each knot had to be pulled tight by wrapping the cord around one's finger, which sometimes cut the operator's fingers until they developed thick calluses.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Logan was convinced there had to be an easier, more forgiving way to accomplish this critical task.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] For the next couple of years, Logan experimented with various tools and materials.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] On June 24, 1958, a patent for the Ty-Rap cable tie was submitted.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Cable ties are generally designed as single-use devices; however, they can be reopened with little or no damage by inserting a small flat object between the ratchet and the pawl, and pulling the pawl out.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Some models have a mechanism to release the pawl and allow re-use.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Alternatively, the tie can be twisted 180 degrees and inserted into the case upside down to create a weaker loop that can be easily opened by hand, but still strong enough for certain simple tasks, such as holding several cables together.
[src:ferrite-bead/cable-tie] Other methods of bundling cable together securely and semi-permanently include cable lacing, strapping, binding knots such as the surgeon's knot or constrictor knot, Velcro brand hook-and-loop strips, conveyor belt hooks, twist ties, Rapstrap fasteners, or metal buckle.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] In electronics, a **choke** is an inductor used to block higher-frequency alternating currents (AC) while passing direct current (DC) and lower-frequency ACs in a circuit.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] A choke usually consists of a coil of insulated wire often wound on a magnetic core, although some consist of a doughnut-shaped ferrite bead strung on a wire.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] The choke's impedance increases with frequency.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Its low electrical resistance passes both AC and DC with little power loss, but its reactance limits the amount of AC passed.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] The name comes from blocking—"choking"—high frequencies while passing low frequencies.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] It is a functional name; the name "choke" is used if an inductor is used for blocking or decoupling higher frequencies, but the component is simply called an "inductor" if used in electronic filters or tuned circuits.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Inductors designed for use as chokes are usually distinguished by not having low-loss construction (high Q factor) required in inductors used in tuned circuits and filtering applications.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Audio frequency chokes usually have ferromagnetic cores to increase their inductance.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] They are often constructed similarly to transformers, with laminated iron cores and an air gap.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] The iron core increases the inductance for a given volume of the core.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Chokes were frequently used in the design of rectifier power supplies for vacuum tube equipment such as radio receivers or amplifiers.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] They are commonly found in direct-current motor controllers to produce direct current (DC), where they were used in conjunction with large electrolytic capacitors to remove the voltage ripple (AC) at the output DC.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] A rectifier circuit designed for a choke-output filter may produce too much DC output voltage and subject the rectifier and filter capacitors to excessive in-rush and ripple currents if the inductor is removed.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] However, modern electrolytic capacitors with high ripple current ratings, and voltage regulators that remove more power supply ripple than chokes could, have eliminated heavy, bulky chokes from mains frequency power supplies.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Smaller chokes are used in switching power supplies to remove the higher-frequency switching transients from the output and sometimes from feeding back into the mains input.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Some car audio hobbyists use choke coils with automobile audio systems (specifically in the wiring of a subwoofer, to remove high frequencies from the amplified signal).
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Radio frequency chokes (RFC) often have iron powder or ferrite cores which increases inductance and overall operation.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] They are often wound in complex patterns (basket winding) to reduce self-capacitance and proximity effect losses.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Chokes for even higher frequencies have non-magnetic cores and low inductance.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] A modern form of choke used for eliminating digital RF noise from lines is the ferrite bead, a cylindrical or torus-shaped core of ferrite slipped over a wire.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] These are often seen on computer cables.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] A common-mode (CM) choke is a special application where a choke is used to act upon a common-mode signal.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] These chokes are useful for suppression of electromagnetic interference (EMI) and radio frequency interference (RFI) frequently introduced on high current wires such as on power supply lines, which may cause unwanted operation.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Reducing this noise is frequently done by using a common mode choke—two parallel coil windings on a single core.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Common mode chokes allow differential currents to pass while blocking signals that are affecting both wires.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Because the magnetic flux produced by differential-mode currents in the core of a common mode choke tend to cancel each other out, the choke presents little impedance to differential mode currents.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] It achieves this by the placement of windings such that they generate equal but opposite fields that cancel each other out for differential mode signals.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] Normally this also means that the core will not saturate for large differential mode currents, and the maximum current rating is instead determined by the heating effect of the winding resistance.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] On the other hand, common mode currents see a high impedance path due to the combined inductance of the windings that reinforce each other.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] CM chokes are commonly used in industrial, electrical and telecommunications applications to remove or decrease noise and related electromagnetic interference.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] When the CM choke is conducting CM current, most of the magnetic flux generated by the windings is confined within the inductor core because of its high permeability.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] In this case, the leakage flux, which is also the near magnetic field emission of the CM choke is low.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] However, the DM current flowing through the windings will generate high emitted near magnetic field since the windings are negative coupled in this case.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] To reduce the near magnetic field emission, a twisted winding structure can be applied to the CM choke.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] The difference between the balanced twisted windings CM choke and conventional balanced two winding CM choke is that the windings interact in the center of the core open window.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] When it is conducting CM current, the balanced twisted winding CM inductor can provide identical CM inductance as the conventional CM inductor.
[src:ferrite-bead/choke-electronics] When it is conducting DM current, the equivalent current loops will generate inversed direction magnetic fields in space so that they tend to cancel each other.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial cable is a type of unbalanced transmission line, used to carry high-frequency electrical signals with low losses.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] It is used in such applications as telephone trunk lines, broadband internet networking cables, high-speed computer data buses, cable television signals, and connecting radio transmitters and receivers to their antennas.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] It differs from other shielded cables because the dimensions of the cable and connectors are controlled to give a precise, constant conductor spacing, which is needed for it to function efficiently as a transmission line.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial cable was used in the first (1858) and following transatlantic cable installations, but its theory was not described until 1880 by English physicist, engineer, and mathematician Oliver Heaviside, who patented the design in that year (British patent No.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial cable is used as a transmission line for radio frequency signals.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Its applications include feedlines connecting radio transmitters and receivers to their antennas, computer network (e.g., Ethernet) connections, digital audio (S/PDIF), and distribution of cable television signals.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] One advantage of coaxial over other types of radio transmission line is that in an ideal coaxial cable the electromagnetic field carrying the signal exists only in the space between the inner and outer conductors.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] This allows coaxial cable runs to be installed next to metal objects such as gutters without the power losses that occur in other types of transmission lines.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial cable also provides protection of the signal from external electromagnetic interference.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial cable conducts electrical signals using an inner conductor (usually a solid copper, stranded copper or copper-plated steel wire) surrounded by an insulating layer and all enclosed by a shield, typically one to four layers of woven metallic braid and metallic tape.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The cable is protected by an outer insulating jacket.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Normally, the outside of the shield is kept at ground potential and a signal carrying voltage is applied to the centre conductor.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] When using differential signaling, coaxial cable provides an advantage of equal push-pull currents on the inner conductor and inside of the outer conductor that restrict the signal's electric and magnetic fields to the dielectric, with little leakage outside the shield.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Further, if at the receiving end, a balun is used to constrain the currents from the inner and outer to equal and opposite, then electric and magnetic fields outside the cable are largely kept from interfering with signals inside the cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] This property makes coaxial cable a good choice both for carrying weak signals that cannot tolerate interference from the environment, and for stronger electrical signals that must not be allowed to radiate or couple into adjacent structures or circuits.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Larger diameter cables and cables with multiple shields have less leakage.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Common applications of coaxial cable include video and CATV distribution, RF and microwave transmission, and computer and instrumentation data connections.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The characteristic impedance of the cable (Z0) is determined by the dielectric constant of the inner insulator and the radii of the inner and outer conductors.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] In radio frequency systems, where the cable length is comparable to the wavelength of the signals transmitted, a uniform cable characteristic impedance is important to minimize loss.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The source and load impedances are chosen to match the impedance of the cable to ensure maximum power transfer and minimum standing wave ratio.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Other important properties of coaxial cable include attenuation as a function of frequency, voltage handling capability, and shield quality.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial cable design choices affect physical size, frequency performance, attenuation, power handling capabilities, flexibility, strength, and cost.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The inner conductor might be solid or stranded; stranded is more flexible.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] To get better high-frequency performance, the inner conductor may be silver-plated.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Copper-plated steel wire is often used as an inner conductor for cable used in the cable TV industry.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The insulator surrounding the inner conductor may be solid plastic, a foam plastic, or air with spacers supporting the inner wire.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The properties of the dielectric insulator determine some of the electrical properties of the cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] A common choice is a solid polyethylene (PE) insulator, used in lower-loss cables.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Solid Teflon (PTFE) is also used as an insulator, and exclusively in plenum-rated cables.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Some coaxial lines use air (or some other gas) and have spacers to keep the inner conductor from touching the shield.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Many conventional coaxial cables use braided copper wire forming the shield.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] This allows the cable to be flexible, but it also means there are gaps in the shield layer, and the inner dimension of the shield varies slightly because the braid cannot be flat.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] For better shield performance, some cables have a double-layer shield.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The shield might be just two braids, but it is more common now to have a thin foil shield covered by a wire braid.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Some cables may invest in more than two shield layers, such as "quad-shield", which uses four alternating layers of foil and braid.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Other shield designs sacrifice flexibility for better performance; some shields are a solid metal tube.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Those cables cannot be bent sharply, as the shield will kink, causing losses in the cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] When a foil shield is used a small wire conductor incorporated into the foil makes soldering the shield termination easier.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] For high-power radio-frequency transmission up to about 1 GHz, coaxial cable with a solid copper outer conductor is available in sizes of 0.25 inch upward.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The outer conductor is corrugated like a bellows to permit flexibility and the inner conductor is held in position by a plastic spiral to approximate an air dielectric.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] One brand name for such cable is *Heliax*.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial cables require an internal structure of an insulating (dielectric) material to maintain the spacing between the centre conductor and shield.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The dielectric losses increase in this order: Ideal dielectric (no loss), vacuum, air, polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE), polyethylene foam, and solid polyethylene.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] An inhomogeneous dielectric needs to be compensated by a non-circular conductor to avoid current hot-spots.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] While many cables have a solid dielectric, many others have a foam dielectric that contains as much air or other gas as possible to reduce the losses by allowing the use of a larger diameter centre conductor.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Foam coax will have about 15% less attenuation but some types of foam dielectric can absorb moisture—especially at its many surfaces—in humid environments, significantly increasing the loss.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Supports shaped like stars or spokes are even better but more expensive and very susceptible to moisture infiltration.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Still more expensive were the air-spaced coaxials used for some inter-city communications in the mid-20th century.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The centre conductor was suspended by polyethylene discs every few centimetres.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] In some low-loss coaxial cables such as the RG-62 type, the inner conductor is supported by a spiral strand of polyethylene, so that an air space exists between most of the conductor and the inside of the jacket.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The lower dielectric constant of air allows for a greater inner diameter at the same impedance and a greater outer diameter at the same cutoff frequency, lowering ohmic losses.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Inner conductors are sometimes silver-plated to smooth the surface and reduce losses due to skin effect.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] A rough surface extends the current path and concentrates the current at peaks, thus increasing ohmic loss.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The insulating jacket can be made from many materials.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] A common choice is PVC, but some applications may require fire-resistant materials.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Outdoor applications may require the jacket to resist ultraviolet light, oxidation, rodent damage, or direct burial.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Flooded coaxial cables use a water-blocking gel to protect the cable from water infiltration through minor cuts in the jacket.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] For internal chassis connections the insulating jacket may be omitted.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Twin-lead transmission lines have the property that the electromagnetic wave propagating down the line extends into the space surrounding the parallel wires.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] These lines have low loss, but also have undesirable characteristics.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] They cannot be bent, tightly twisted, or otherwise shaped without changing their characteristic impedance, causing reflection of the signal back toward the source.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] They also cannot be buried or run along or attached to anything conductive, as the extended fields will induce currents in the nearby conductors causing unwanted radiation and detuning of the line.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Standoff insulators are used to keep them away from parallel metal surfaces.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial lines largely solve this problem by confining virtually all of the electromagnetic wave to the area inside the cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial lines can therefore be bent and moderately twisted without negative effects, and they can be strapped to conductive supports without inducing unwanted currents in them, so long as provisions are made to ensure differential signalling push-pull currents in the cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] In radio-frequency applications up to a few gigahertz, the wave propagates primarily in the transverse electric magnetic (TEM) mode, which means that the electric and magnetic fields are both perpendicular to the direction of propagation.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] However, above a certain cutoff frequency, transverse electric (TE) or transverse magnetic (TM) modes can also propagate, as they do in a hollow waveguide.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] It is usually undesirable to transmit signals above the cutoff frequency, since it may cause multiple modes with different phase velocities to propagate, interfering with each other.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The outer diameter is roughly inversely proportional to the cutoff frequency.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] A propagating surface-wave mode that only involves the central conductor also exists, but is effectively suppressed in coaxial cable of conventional geometry and common impedance.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Electric field lines for this TM mode have a longitudinal component and require line lengths of a half-wavelength or longer.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial cable may be viewed as a type of waveguide.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Power is transmitted through the radial electric field and the circumferential magnetic field in the TEM mode.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] This is the dominant mode from zero frequency (DC) to an upper limit determined by the electrical dimensions of the cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial connectors are designed to maintain a coaxial form across the connection and have the same impedance as the attached cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Connectors are usually plated with high-conductivity metals such as silver or tarnish-resistant gold.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Due to the skin effect, the RF signal is only carried by the plating at higher frequencies and does not penetrate to the connector body.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Silver however tarnishes quickly and the silver sulfide that is produced is poorly conductive, degrading connector performance, making silver a poor choice for this application.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial cable is a particular kind of transmission line, so the circuit models developed for general transmission lines are appropriate.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The best coaxial cable impedances were experimentally determined at Bell Laboratories in 1929 to be 77 Ω for low-attenuation, 60 Ω for high-voltage, and 30 Ω for high-power.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] For a coaxial cable with air dielectric and a shield of a given inner diameter, the attenuation is minimized by choosing the diameter of the inner conductor to give a characteristic impedance of 76.7 Ω.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] When more common dielectrics are considered, the lowest insertion loss impedance drops down to a value between 52 and 64 Ω.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Maximum power handling is achieved at 30 Ω.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The approximate impedance required to match a centre-fed dipole antenna in free space (i.e., a dipole without ground reflections) is 73 Ω, so 75 Ω coax was commonly used for connecting shortwave antennas to receivers.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] These typically involve such low levels of RF power that power-handling and high-voltage breakdown characteristics are unimportant when compared to attenuation.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Likewise with CATV, although many broadcast TV installations and CATV headends use 300 Ω folded dipole antennas to receive off-the-air signals, 75 Ω coax makes a convenient 4:1 balun transformer for these as well as possessing low attenuation.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The arithmetic mean between 30 Ω and 77 Ω is 53.5 Ω; the geometric mean is 48 Ω.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The selection of 50 Ω as a compromise between power-handling capability and attenuation is in general cited as the reason for the number.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] 50 Ω also works out tolerably well because it corresponds approximately to the feedpoint impedance of a half-wave dipole, mounted approximately a half-wave above "normal" ground (ideally 73 Ω, but reduced for low-hanging horizontal wires).
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] RG-62 is a 93 Ω coaxial cable originally used in mainframe computer networks in the 1970s and early 1980s (it was the cable used to connect IBM 3270 terminals to IBM 3274/3174 terminal cluster controllers).
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Later, some manufacturers of LAN equipment, such as Datapoint for ARCNET, adopted RG-62 as their coaxial cable standard.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The cable has the lowest capacitance per unit-length when compared to other coaxial cables of similar size.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] All of the components of a coaxial system should have the same impedance to avoid internal reflections at connections between components (see Impedance matching).
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Such reflections may cause signal attenuation.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] They introduce standing waves, which increase losses and can even result in cable dielectric breakdown with high-power transmission.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] In analog video or TV systems, reflections cause ghosting in the image; multiple reflections may cause the original signal to be followed by more than one echo.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] If a coaxial cable is open (not connected at the end), the termination has nearly infinite resistance, which causes reflections.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] If the coaxial cable is short-circuited, the termination resistance is nearly zero, which causes reflections with the opposite polarity.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Reflections will be nearly eliminated if the coaxial cable is terminated in a pure resistance equal to its impedance.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Signal leakage is the passage of electromagnetic fields through the shield of a cable and occurs in both directions.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Ingress is the passage of an outside signal into the cable and can result in noise and disruption of the desired signal.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Egress is the passage of signal intended to remain within the cable into the outside world and can result in a weaker signal at the end of the cable and radio frequency interference to nearby devices.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Severe leakage usually results from improperly installed connectors or faults in the cable shield.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] For example, in the United States, signal leakage from cable television systems is regulated by the FCC, since cable signals use the same frequencies as aeronautical and radionavigation bands.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] CATV operators may also choose to monitor their networks for leakage to prevent ingress.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Outside signals entering the cable can cause unwanted noise and picture ghosting.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Excessive noise can overwhelm the signal, making it useless.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] In-channel ingress can be digitally removed by ingress cancellation.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] An ideal shield would be a perfect conductor with no holes, gaps, or bumps connected to a perfect ground.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] However, a smooth solid highly conductive shield would be heavy, inflexible, and expensive.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Such coax is used for straight-line feeds to commercial radio broadcast towers.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] More economical cables must make compromises between shield efficacy, flexibility, and cost, such as the corrugated surface of flexible hardline, flexible braid, or foil shields.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Since shields cannot be perfect conductors, current flowing on the inside of the shield produces an electromagnetic field on the outer surface of the shield.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The magnitude of an alternating current in a conductor decays exponentially with distance beneath the surface, with the depth of penetration being proportional to the square root of the resistivity.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] This means that, in a shield of finite thickness, some small amount of current will still be flowing on the opposite surface of the conductor.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] With a perfect conductor (i.e., zero resistivity), all of the current would flow at the surface, with no penetration into and through the conductor.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Real cables have a shield made of an imperfect, although usually very good, conductor, so there must always be some leakage.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The gaps or holes, allow some of the electromagnetic field to penetrate to the other side.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] For example, braided shields have many small gaps.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The gaps are smaller when using a foil (solid metal) shield, but there is still a seam running the length of the cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Foil becomes increasingly rigid with increasing thickness, so a thin foil layer is often surrounded by a layer of braided metal, which offers greater flexibility for a given cross-section.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Signal leakage can be severe if there is poor contact at the interface to connectors at either end of the cable or if there is a break in the shield.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] To greatly reduce signal leakage into or out of the cable, by a factor of 1000, or even 10,000, superscreened cables are often used in critical applications, such as for neutron flux counters in nuclear reactors.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Superscreened cables for nuclear use are defined in IEC 96-4-1, 1990, however as there have been long gaps in the construction of nuclear power stations in Europe, many existing installations are using superscreened cables to the UK standard AESS(TRG) 71181 which is referenced in IEC 61917.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] A continuous current, even if small, along the imperfect shield of a coaxial cable can cause visible or audible interference.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] In CATV systems distributing analog signals the potential difference between the coaxial network and the electrical grounding system of a house can cause a visible "hum bar" in the picture.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] This appears as a wide horizontal distortion bar in the picture that scrolls slowly upward.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Such differences in potential can be reduced by proper bonding to a common ground at the house.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] External fields create a voltage across the inductance of the outside of the outer conductor between sender and receiver.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The effect is less when there are several parallel cables, as this reduces the inductance and, therefore, the voltage.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Because the outer conductor carries the reference potential for the signal on the inner conductor, the receiving circuit measures the wrong voltage.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The transformer effect is sometimes used to mitigate the effect of currents induced in the shield.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The inner and outer conductors form the primary and secondary winding of the transformer, and the effect is enhanced in some high-quality cables that have an outer layer of mu-metal.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Because of this 1:1 transformer, the aforementioned voltage across the outer conductor is transformed onto the inner conductor so that the two voltages can be cancelled by the receiver.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Many senders and receivers have means to reduce the leakage even further.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] They increase the transformer effect by passing the whole cable through a ferrite core one or more times.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Common mode current occurs when stray currents in the shield flow in the same direction as the current in the centre conductor, causing the coax to radiate.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] They are the opposite of the desired "push-pull" differential signalling currents, where the signal currents on the inner and outer conductor are equal and opposite.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Most of the shield effect in coax results from opposing currents in the centre conductor and shield creating opposite magnetic fields that cancel, and thus do not radiate.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] However, ladder line is extremely sensitive to surrounding metal objects, which can enter the fields before they completely cancel.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coax does not have this problem, since the field is enclosed in the shield.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] However, it is still possible for a field to form between the shield and other connected objects, such as the antenna the coax feeds.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The current formed by the field between the antenna and the coax shield would flow in the same direction as the current in the centre conductor, and thus not be canceled.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Energy would radiate from the coax itself, affecting the radiation pattern of the antenna.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] With sufficient power, this could be a hazard to people near the cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] A properly placed and properly sized balun can prevent common-mode radiation in coax.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] An isolating transformer or blocking capacitor can be used to couple a coaxial cable to equipment, where it is desirable to pass radio-frequency signals but to block direct current or low-frequency power.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The velocity of propagation also decreases considerably.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Thus coaxial-cable impedances are consistent at RF frequencies but variable across audio frequencies.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] This effect was manifested when trying to send a plain voice signal across the transatlantic telegraph cable, with poor results.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] A thinner version, with some of the electrical characteristics of RG-8U in a diameter similar to RG-59.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Low loss at high frequency for cable and satellite television.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Used for long drops and underground conduit, similar to RG7 but generally lower loss.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] In general, it has poor shielding but will carry an HQ HD signal or video over short distances.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Similar physical characteristics as RG-59 and RG-59/U, but with a higher velocity factor.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Used to carry television, video observation systems, and other.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Used for interior lines for monitoring system, CCTV feeder lines, wiring between the camera and control unit and video signal transmission.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Used for high-definition cable TV and high-speed cable Internet.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Used for high-frequency signal transmission.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Short coaxial cables are commonly used to connect home video equipment, in ham radio setups, and in Nuclear Instrumentation Modules.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] While formerly common for implementing computer networks, in particular Ethernet ("thick" 10BASE5 and "thin" 10BASE2), twisted pair cables have replaced them in most applications except in the consumer cable modem market for broadband Internet access.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Long distance coaxial cable was used in the 20th century to connect radio networks, television networks, and long-distance telephone networks though this has largely been superseded by later methods (fibre optics, T1/E1, satellite).
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Shorter coaxials still carry cable television signals to the majority of television receivers, and this purpose consumes the majority of coaxial cable production.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] In 1980s and early 1990s coaxial cable was also used in computer networking, most prominently in Ethernet networks, where it was later in late 1990s to early 2000s replaced by UTP cables in North America and STP cables in Western Europe, both with 8P8C modular connectors.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Micro coaxial cables are used in a range of consumer devices, military equipment, and also in ultrasound scanning equipment.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The most common impedances that are widely used are 50 or 52 ohms and 75 ohms, although other impedances are available for specific applications.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] The 50 / 52 ohm cables are widely used for industrial and commercial two-way radio frequency applications (including radio, and telecommunications), although 75 ohms is commonly used for broadcast television and radio.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] Coaxial cable is often used to carry signals from an antenna to a receiver.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] In many cases, the same cable carries power toward the antenna, to power a preamplifier.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p01] In some cases, a single cable carries unidirectional power and bidirectional data/signals, as in DiSEqC.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] Larger varieties of hardline may have a centre conductor that is constructed from either rigid or corrugated copper tubing.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] The dielectric in hard line may consist of polyethylene foam, air, or a pressurized gas such as nitrogen or desiccated air (dried air).
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] In gas-charged lines, hard plastics such as nylon are used as spacers to separate the inner and outer conductors.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] The addition of these gases into the dielectric space reduces moisture contamination, provides a stable dielectric constant, and provides a reduced risk of internal arcing.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] Gas-filled hardlines are usually used on high-power RF transmitters such as television or radio broadcasting, military transmitters, and high-power amateur radio applications but may also be used on some critical lower-power applications such as those in the microwave bands.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] However, in the microwave region, *waveguide* is more often used than hard line for transmitter-to-antenna, or antenna-to-receiver applications.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] The various shields used in hard line also differ; some forms use rigid tubing, or pipe, while others may use a corrugated tubing, which makes bending easier, as well as reduces kinking when the cable is bent to conform.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] Smaller varieties of hard line may be used internally in some high-frequency applications, in particular in equipment within the microwave range, to reduce interference between stages of the device.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] Conformable cable is a flexible reformable alternative to semi-rigid coaxial cable used where flexibility is required.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] Conformable cable can be stripped and formed by hand without the need for specialized tools, similar to standard coaxial cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] Coaxial cable insulation may degrade, requiring replacement of the cable, especially if it has been exposed to the elements on a continuous basis.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] The shield is normally grounded, and if even a single thread of the braid or filament of foil touches the centre conductor, the signal will be shorted causing significant or total signal loss.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] This most often occurs at improperly installed end connectors and splices.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] Also, the connector or splice must be properly attached to the shield, as this provides the path to ground for the interfering signal.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] Despite being shielded, interference can occur on coaxial cable lines.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] Susceptibility to interference has little relationship to broad cable type designations (e.g.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] RG-59, RG-6) but is strongly related to the composition and configuration of the cable's shielding.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] For cable television, with frequencies extending well into the UHF range, a foil shield is normally provided, and will provide total coverage as well as high effectiveness against high-frequency interference.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] Foil shielding is ordinarily accompanied by a tinned copper or aluminium braid shield, with anywhere from 60 to 95% coverage.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] The braid is important to shield effectiveness because (1) it is more effective than foil at preventing low-frequency interference, (2) it provides higher conductivity to ground than foil, and (3) it makes attaching a connector easier and more reliable.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] In the United States and some other countries, cable television distribution systems use extensive networks of outdoor coaxial cable, often with in-line distribution amplifiers.
[src:ferrite-bead/coax-p02] Leakage of signals into and out of cable TV systems can cause interference to cable subscribers and to over-the-air radio services using the same frequencies as those of the cable system.
[src:ferrite-bead/decoupling-electronics] In electronics, **decoupling** is the prevention of undesired electrical energy transfer (coupling) between subsystems.
[src:ferrite-bead/decoupling-electronics] A common example is connecting localized decoupling capacitors close to the power leads of integrated circuits to suppress coupling via the power supply connections.
[src:ferrite-bead/decoupling-electronics] These act as a small localized energy reservoir that supply the circuit with current during transient, high current demand periods, preventing the voltage on the power supply rail from being pulled down by the momentary current load.
[src:ferrite-bead/decoupling-electronics] Another common example of the use of decoupling capacitors is across the emitter bias resistor of transistor common emitter amplifiers to prevent the resistor absorbing a portion of the AC output power of the amplifier.
[src:ferrite-bead/decoupling-electronics] Lossy ferrite beads may also be used to isolate or 'island' sections of circuitry.
[src:ferrite-bead/decoupling-electronics] These add a high series impedance (in contrast to the low parallel impedance added by decoupling capacitors) to the power supply rails, preventing high-frequency currents being drawn from elsewhere in the system.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In electrical engineering, **impedance** is the opposition to alternating current presented by the combined effect of resistance and reactance in a circuit.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Quantitatively, the impedance of a two-terminal circuit element is the ratio of the complex representation of the sinusoidal voltage between its terminals, to the complex representation of the current flowing through it.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In general, it depends upon the frequency of the sinusoidal voltage.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Impedance extends the concept of resistance to alternating current (AC) circuits, and possesses both magnitude and phase, unlike resistance, which has only magnitude.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Impedance can be represented as a complex number, with the same units as resistance, for which the SI unit is the ohm (Ω).
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Its symbol is usually *Z*, and it may be represented by writing its magnitude and phase in the polar form |*Z*|*∠θ*.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] However, Cartesian complex number representation is often more powerful for circuit analysis purposes.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The notion of impedance is useful for performing AC analysis of electrical networks, because it allows relating sinusoidal voltages and currents by a simple linear law.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In multiple port networks, the two-terminal definition of impedance is inadequate, but the complex voltages at the ports and the currents flowing through them are still linearly related by the impedance matrix.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The reciprocal of impedance is admittance, whose SI unit is the siemens.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Instruments used to measure the electrical impedance are called impedance analyzers.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Perhaps the earliest use of complex numbers in circuit analysis was by Johann Victor Wietlisbach in 1879 in analysing the Maxwell bridge.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Wietlisbach avoided using differential equations by expressing AC currents and voltages as exponential functions with imaginary exponents (see § Validity of complex representation).
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Wietlisbach found the required voltage was given by multiplying the current by a complex number (impedance), although he did not identify this as a general parameter in its own right.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The term *impedance* was coined by Oliver Heaviside in July 1886.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Heaviside recognised that the "resistance operator" (impedance) in his operational calculus was a complex number.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In 1887 he showed that there was an AC equivalent to Ohm's law.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Arthur Kennelly published an influential paper on impedance in 1893.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Kennelly arrived at a complex number representation in a rather more direct way than using imaginary exponential functions.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Kennelly followed the graphical representation of impedance (showing resistance, reactance, and impedance as the lengths of the sides of a right angle triangle) developed by John Ambrose Fleming in 1889.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Impedances could thus be added vectorially.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Kennelly realised that this graphical representation of impedance was directly analogous to graphical representation of complex numbers (Argand diagram).
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Problems in impedance calculation could thus be approached algebraically with a complex number representation.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Later that same year, Kennelly's work was generalised to all AC circuits by Charles Proteus Steinmetz.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Steinmetz not only represented impedances by complex numbers but also voltages and currents.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Unlike Kennelly, Steinmetz was thus able to express AC equivalents of DC laws such as Ohm's and Kirchhoff's laws.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Steinmetz's work was highly influential in spreading the technique amongst engineers.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In addition to resistance as seen in DC circuits, impedance in AC circuits includes the effects of the induction of voltages in conductors by the magnetic fields (inductance), and the electrostatic storage of charge induced by voltages between conductors (capacitance).
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The impedance caused by these two effects is collectively referred to as reactance and forms the imaginary part of complex impedance whereas resistance forms the real part.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The impedance of a two-terminal circuit element is represented as a complex quantity Z .
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] where the magnitude $|Z|$ represents the ratio of the voltage difference amplitude to the amplitude of the current, while the argument $\arg(Z)$ (commonly given the symbol $\theta$ ) gives the phase difference between voltage and current.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In electrical engineering, the letter i is used for electric current, so the imaginary unit is instead represented by the letter j .
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] where the real part of impedance is the resistance R and the imaginary part is the reactance X.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Where it is needed to add or subtract impedances, the cartesian form is more convenient; but when quantities are multiplied or divided, the calculation becomes simpler if the polar form is used.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] A circuit calculation, such as finding the total impedance of two impedances in parallel, may require conversion between forms several times during the calculation.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Conversion between the forms follows the normal conversion rules of complex numbers.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] To simplify calculations, sinusoidal voltage and current waves are commonly represented as complex-valued functions of time denoted as V and I .
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The magnitude equation is the familiar Ohm's law applied to the voltage and current amplitudes, while the second equation defines the phase relationship.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The real-valued sinusoidal function representing either voltage or current may be broken into two complex-valued functions.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] By the principle of superposition, we may analyse the behaviour of the sinusoid on the left-hand side by analysing the behaviour of the two complex terms on the right-hand side.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Given the symmetry, we only need to perform the analysis for one right-hand term.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The results are identical for the other.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The meaning of electrical impedance can be understood by substituting it into Ohm's law.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The magnitude of the impedance $|Z|$ acts just like resistance, giving the drop in voltage amplitude across an impedance Z for a given current I .
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The phase factor tells us that the current lags the voltage by a phase $\theta =\arg(Z)$ (i.e., in the time domain, the current signal is shifted ${\textstyle {\frac {\theta }{2\pi }}T}$ later with respect to the voltage signal).
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Just as impedance extends Ohm's law to cover AC circuits, other results from DC circuit analysis, such as voltage division, current division, Thévenin's theorem and Norton's theorem, can also be extended to AC circuits by replacing resistance with impedance.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] A phasor is represented by a constant complex number, usually expressed in exponential form, representing the complex amplitude (magnitude and phase) of a sinusoidal function of time.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Phasors are used by electrical engineers to simplify computations involving sinusoids (such as in AC circuits), where they can often reduce a differential equation problem to an algebraic one.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The impedance of a circuit element can be defined as the ratio of the phasor voltage across the element to the phasor current through the element, as determined by the relative amplitudes and phases of the voltage and current.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] This is identical to the definition from Ohm's law given above, recognising that the factors of $e^{j\omega t}$ cancel.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In this case, the voltage and current waveforms are proportional and in phase.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In both cases, for an applied sinusoidal voltage, the resulting current is also sinusoidal, but in quadrature, 90 degrees out of phase with the voltage.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] However, the phases have opposite signs: in an inductor, the current is *lagging*; in a capacitor the current is *leading*.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The magnitude gives the change in voltage amplitude for a given current amplitude through the impedance, while the exponential factors give the phase relationship.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] What follows below is a derivation of impedance for each of the three basic circuit elements: the resistor, the capacitor, and the inductor.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Although the idea can be extended to define the relationship between the voltage and current of any arbitrary signal, these derivations assume sinusoidal signals.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In fact, this applies to any arbitrary periodic signals, because these can be approximated as a sum of sinusoids through Fourier analysis.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] This says that the ratio of AC voltage amplitude to alternating current (AC) amplitude across a resistor is R , and that the AC voltage leads the current across a resistor by 0 degrees.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] As in the case of capacitors, it is also possible to derive this formula directly from the complex representations of the voltages and currents, or by assuming a sinusoidal voltage between the two poles of the inductor.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In the latter case, integrating the differential equation above leads to a constant term for the current, that represents a fixed DC bias flowing through the inductor.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] This is set to zero because AC analysis using frequency domain impedance considers one frequency at a time and DC represents a separate frequency of zero hertz in this context.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The impedance of capacitors and inductors were defined above in terms of *$j\omega$*, but this simplification can strictly be applied only to circuits that are driven with steady state AC and DC signals, a condition called the *steady state*.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The mere act of turning a signal source ON or OFF violates this steady state condition.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] To allow evaluation of the transient response in addition to the steady state of a circuit, the concept of impedance can be extended to a circuit energised with any arbitrary signal by using complex frequency $s{=}\sigma {+}j\omega$ instead of just $j\omega$ .
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Signals are expressed in terms of complex frequency by taking the Laplace transform of the time domain expression of the signal.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] For a steady state signal, s simplifies to $j\omega$ .
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] This further simplifies to $s{=}0$ for a DC-only circuit, in which case every inductor will behave as a short circuit and every capacitor will behave as an open circuit.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The impedance Z of an electrical component is defined as the ratio between the Laplace transforms of the voltage over it and the current through it, i.e.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] where $s=\sigma +j\omega$ is the complex Laplace parameter.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The phasor domain is sometimes dubbed the frequency domain, although it lacks one of the dimensions of the Laplace parameter.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] For steady-state, the polar form of the complex impedance relates the amplitude and phase of the voltage and current.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] These two relationships hold even after taking the real part of the complex exponentials (see phasors), which is the part of the signal one actually measures in real-life circuits.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In many applications, the relative phase of the voltage and current is not critical so only the magnitude of the impedance is significant.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Resistance R is the real part of impedance; a device with a purely resistive impedance exhibits no phase shift between the voltage and current.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Reactance X is the imaginary part of the impedance; a component with a finite reactance induces a phase shift $\theta$ between the voltage across it and the current through it.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] A purely reactive component is distinguished by the sinusoidal voltage across the component being in quadrature with the sinusoidal current through the component.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] This implies that the component alternately absorbs energy from the circuit and then returns energy to the circuit.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] A pure reactance does not dissipate any power.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] A capacitor has a purely reactive impedance that is inversely proportional to the signal frequency.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] A capacitor consists of two conductors separated by an insulator, also known as a dielectric.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The minus sign indicates that the imaginary part of the impedance is negative.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] At low frequencies, a capacitor approaches an open circuit so no current flows through it.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] A DC voltage applied across a capacitor causes charge to accumulate on one side; the electric field due to the accumulated charge is the source of the opposition to the current.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] When the potential associated with the charge exactly balances the applied voltage, the current goes to zero.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Driven by an AC supply, a capacitor accumulates only a limited charge before the potential difference changes sign and the charge dissipates.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The higher the frequency, the less charge accumulates and the smaller the opposition to the current.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Inductive reactance $X_{L}$ is proportional to the signal frequency f and the inductance L .
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] An inductor consists of a coiled conductor.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction gives the back emf ${\mathcal {E}}$ (voltage opposing current) due to a rate-of-change of magnetic flux density B through a current loop.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The back-emf is the source of the opposition to current flow.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] A constant direct current has a zero rate-of-change, and sees an inductor as a short-circuit (it is typically made from a material with a low resistivity).
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] An alternating current has a time-averaged rate-of-change that is proportional to frequency, this causes the increase in inductive reactance with frequency.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The total impedance of many simple networks of components can be calculated using the rules for combining impedances in series and parallel.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The rules are identical to those for combining resistances, except that the numbers in general are complex numbers.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The general case, however, requires equivalent impedance transforms in addition to series and parallel.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] For components connected in series, the current through each circuit element is the same; the total impedance is the sum of the component impedances.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] For components connected in parallel, the voltage across each circuit element is the same; the ratio of currents through any two elements is the inverse ratio of their impedances.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The equivalent impedance $Z_{\text{eq}}$ can be calculated in terms of the equivalent series resistance $R_{\text{eq}}$ and reactance $X_{\text{eq}}$ .
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The measurement of the impedance of devices and transmission lines is a practical problem in radio technology and other fields.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Measurements of impedance may be carried out at one frequency, or the variation of device impedance over a range of frequencies may be of interest.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The impedance may be measured or displayed directly in ohms, or other values related to impedance may be displayed; for example, in a radio antenna, the standing wave ratio or reflection coefficient may be more useful than the impedance alone.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The measurement of impedance requires the measurement of the magnitude of voltage and current, and the phase difference between them.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Impedance is often measured by "bridge" methods, similar to the direct-current Wheatstone bridge; a calibrated reference impedance is adjusted to balance off the effect of the impedance of the device under test.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Impedance measurement in power electronic devices may require simultaneous measurement and provision of power to the operating device.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The impedance of a device can be calculated by complex division of the voltage and current.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The impedance of the device can be calculated by applying a sinusoidal voltage to the device in series with a resistor, and measuring the voltage across the resistor and across the device.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] Performing this measurement by sweeping the frequencies of the applied signal provides the impedance phase and magnitude.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The use of an impulse response may be used in combination with the fast Fourier transform (FFT) to rapidly measure the electrical impedance of various electrical devices.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] The LCR meter measures a component's inductance (L), capacitance (C), and resistance (R); from these values, the impedance at any frequency can be calculated.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] In general, neither impedance nor admittance can vary with time, since they are defined for complex exponentials in which −∞ < *t* < +∞.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] If the complex exponential voltage to current ratio changes over time or amplitude, the circuit element cannot be described using the frequency domain.
[src:ferrite-bead/electrical-impedance] This description is an approximation: Over large signal swings or wide observation windows, the voltage to current relationship will not be LTI and cannot be described by impedance.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] A **ferrite bead** – also called a **ferrite block**, **ferrite core**, **ferrite ring**, **EMI filter**, or **ferrite choke** – is a type of choke that suppresses high-frequency electronic noise in electronic circuits.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads employ high-frequency current dissipation in a ferrite ceramic to build high-frequency noise suppression devices.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads prevent electromagnetic interference (EMI) in two directions: *from* a device or *to* a device.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] A conductive cable acts as an antenna – if the device produces radio-frequency energy, this can be *transmitted* through the cable, which acts as an unintentional radiator.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] In this case, the bead is required for regulatory compliance to reduce EMI.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Conversely, if there are other sources of EMI, such as household appliances, the bead prevents the cable from acting as an antenna and *receiving* interference from these other devices.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] This is particularly common on data cables and medical equipment.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Large ferrite beads are commonly seen on external cabling.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] In addition, various smaller ferrite beads are used internally in circuits—on conductors or around the pins of small circuit-board components, such as transistors, connectors, and integrated circuits.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Beads can block low-level unintended radio frequency energy on wires intended to be DC conductors by acting as a low-pass filter.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] For example, on unbalanced coax transmission lines (such as video cables), the cable is designed to contain the signal, and beads can be used to block stray common mode current from using the cable as an antenna while not interfering with the signal carried inside the cable.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] In this use, the bead is a simple form of a balun.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads are one of the simplest and least expensive interference filters to install on preexisting electronic cabling.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] For a simple ferrite ring, the wire is wrapped around the core through the center, typically five or seven times.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Clamp-on cores are also available, which attach without wrapping the wire: this type of ferrite core is usually designed so that the wire passes only once through it.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] If the fit is not snug enough, the core can be secured with cable ties, or if the center is large enough, the cabling can loop through one or more times.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] (However, although each loop increases the impedance to high frequencies, it also shifts the frequency of the highest impedance to a lower frequency.) Small ferrite beads can be slipped over component leads to suppress parasitic oscillation.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Surface-mount ferrite beads are available.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Like any other surface-mount inductor, these are soldered into a gap in the printed circuit board trace.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Inside the bead component, a coil of wire runs between layers of ferrite to form a multi-turn inductor around the high-permeability core.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads are used as a passive low-pass filter by dissipating radio frequency (RF) energy as heat by design.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Ideal inductors, on the other hand, have no resistance and hence do not dissipate energy as heat.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Ideal inductors only have inductive reactance, which reduces the flow of high-frequency signals by returning some of their energy back towards the signal source (possibly reducing the amount of power drawn) rather than dissipating that energy as heat (as done by the resistance in ferrite beads).
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] While an inductor's reactance may commonly be referred to simply as *impedance*, impedance generally can be any combination of resistance and reactance.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] The geometry and electromagnetic properties of coiled wire over the ferrite bead result in an impedance for high-frequency signals, attenuating high-frequency EMI/RFI electronic noise.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] The energy is either reflected back up the cable or dissipated as low-level heat.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Only in extreme cases is the heat noticeable.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] A ferrite bead can be added to an inductor to improve, in two ways, its ability to block unwanted high frequency noise.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] First, the ferrite concentrates the magnetic field, increasing inductance and, therefore, reactance, which filters out the noise.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Second, if the ferrite is so designed, it can produce an additional loss in the form of resistance in the ferrite itself.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] The ferrite creates an inductor with a very low Q factor.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] This loss heats the ferrite, generally by a negligible amount.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] While the signal level is large enough to cause interference or undesirable effects in sensitive circuits, the energy blocked is typically relatively small.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Depending on the application, the resistive loss characteristic of the ferrite may or may not be desired.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] A design that uses a ferrite bead to improve noise filtering must consider specific circuit characteristics and the frequency range to block.
[src:ferrite-bead/ferrite-bead] Different ferrite materials have different properties concerning frequency, and the manufacturer's literature helps select the most effective material for the frequency range.
